climate change will push an additional 100 million people back into poverty by 
2030 and that South Asia will be hardest hit. This will be a major threat to 
achieving several SDGs, and not least goal 6 on water and sanitation. This is 
particularly concerning for the coastal areas of Southwest Bangladesh, where 
cyclones Sidr (2006) and Aila (2009) shattered infrastructures and livelihood 
opportunities, and many of those affected are yet to recover. Drinking water 
and sanitation scarcity is still severe following those disasters, leading to 
poor hygiene behaviour. This is having a severe impact on the livelihoods and health 
of communities in the project area, and in particular on women and girls.&nbsp; During the dry season, women and girls travel 
3 to 4 km to fetch water – water, which is not even safe to drink – leaving 
less time for income-generating activities and education. Furthermore, many 
families are left without male family members, who are to migrate to find work. 
Adding to this, high salt levels and hydrological conditions caused by climate 
change in coastal areas are creating technological challenges to the supply of 
safe water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH). Saline levels are particularly 
problematic in the project area, with levels increasing in both surface and 
groundwater. As a result, some technologies are no longer working and there is 
subsequently an acute need for new solutions that can withstand climate change. 
Proposed project will improve WASH security for 75,000 climate vulnerable 
people (70% of which are women and children) in coastal areas on the southwest 
of Bangladesh, by strengthening the resilience of WASH facilities. This will be 
achieved by testing and evolving climate resilient technologies; increasing 
sustainable access to safe drinking water and sanitation; improving hygiene 
behaviour; and increasing local capacity of communities and local governments 
to maintain facilities. This will contribute to Bangladesh achieving universal 
access to safe water and sanitation by 2030 (SDG6), which will in turn 
facilitate the achievement of&nbsp; goals 
related to poverty (SDG1), good health (SDG3), quality education (SDG4), gender 
equality (SDG5).&nbsp;Aligning with programmatic objectives, this project intended to achieve 
five specific changes: increase access to safe water and improved sanitation 
for poor and excluded in climate vulnerable area, proper hygiene practice among 
household members and school children improved, increase awareness on climate 
resilience and water safety compliance, improve resilience and inclusive WASH 
facilities at institutions and public places, improve leadership role of local 
government institutes in planning, coordinating and monitoring WASH services.</span></p> <h2><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font><font style="font-size: 12pt;" face="Arial,sans-serif">2. What?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font>&nbsp;<strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Project theme</font></strong><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;– This project will promote 
