diverse landscape and semi-arid climate. The region has been experiencing 
recurrent below-average rainfall and thus lowering of groundwater levels in 
aquifers along with surface water flow reduction leading to water crisis for 
household, industry and agriculture. Apart from this the changed climatic 
condition has been posing a serious threat for which water crisis becoming more 
frequent, more intense, more spatially extensive, and of longer duration. A 
typical dry climate with comparatively high temperature (ranging from 25-45 degree Celsius) prevails here with severe water scarcity during 4-5 months 
of the year.Depending on its hydro-geology and aquifer materials, ground water of the 
project area is mainly recharged by the rainwater infiltration. A gradual 
declining of groundwater level during dry season without full recovery during 
wet season, delayed monsoon, less rainfall, drying rivers have been 
contributing to present water crisis. Groundwater level is continuously 
lowering at the rate of 1.37 ft/y in wet season and 0.72 ft/y in dry season. 
Recurrent shortage of surface water and ground water has posed several impacts 
that can be categorized as economic, social, environmental and hygienic. Water 
dependent sanitation options become unhygienic due to water scarcity and a 
large part of the poor and hard core poor population cannot afford to have 
expensive options regarding this.&nbsp;Most of the water management projects in this area mainly focus on flood control, drainage and agricultural production, ignoring 
availability of safe water for domestic consumption. Integration between integrated 
water resources management and WASH as human rights is largely absent in water 
projects.&nbsp;In this context, there is a need for an 
integrated community-based management process backed by improved knowledge, 
informed and skilled community members, LGIs and other duty bearers who are 
able to manage water project with equity, efficiency and sustainability.&nbsp;This project is built on the premises that 
acknowledge WASH as an integral part of IWRM approach, which provides a 
framework for action to adapt climate change impacts on water resources 
management. This indicates an urgent effort for resilient WASH facilities, 
local knowledge and awareness, innovative technology and community practices, 
capacity building, good governance and commitment from the stakeholders. The essence 
of such integration (WASH in IWRM) is clearly spelled out in SDG 6.&nbsp; Implementation of the project will 
follow a community based bottom-up approach and takes sequenced steps to 
understand and respond to the challenges of the local context: first, 
understanding the ground reality through primary and secondary research; then 
capacity building and raising awareness in the community and instigating 
collective action through innovative participatory mechanisms; and finally, 
taking the lessons from these practices forward into local and national 
policy making and research. Following major activities will constitute the main 
building blocks of the project. Aligning with programmatic objectives, this project intended to achieve 
five specific changes: increase access to safe water and improved sanitation 
for poor and excluded in climate vulnerable area, proper hygiene practice among 
household members and school children improved, increase awareness on climate 
resilience and water safety compliance, improve resilience and inclusive WASH 
facilities at institutions and public places, improve leadership role of local 
government institutes in planning, coordinating and monitoring WASH services.<br></span></p> <h2><span color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 16px;"></span><span face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 16px;">2. What?</span></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Project theme</font></strong><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;– Proposed project will try to promote resiliency for WASH services with 
addressing rights for vulnerable people in drought prone area through building capacity and empowering community, local government and 
duty bearer to develop context specific technology, approach and adaptive 
planning in an integrated manner with multi-sectoral coordination. In this 
project number of innovative and challenging approach and tools like integrated 
water resources management (IWRM) and water use efficiency and water reuse will 
be introduced.</font><br><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Estimated cost</font></strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">&nbsp;– &nbsp;GBP 600,150. This is fully unfunded.</font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Estimated timeframe</font></strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">&nbsp;– 36 months</font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Existing WaterAid experience</font></strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">&nbsp;– More than 2 years’ experience</font></p> <h2><font style="font-size: 12pt;" face="Arial,sans-serif">3. Where?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font><span style="font-size: 16px;">This project will be implemented in Godagari upazila of Rajshahi district of this Barind area. Total 
