ing: 0cm 5.4pt; border-width: medium 1pt 1pt; border-style: none solid solid; border-right: 1pt solid rgb(127, 127, 127); border-bottom: 1pt solid rgb(127, 127, 127); border-left: 1pt solid rgb(127, 127, 127); text-align: left;"> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Approved by</font></strong></p> </td> <td width="27%" valign="top" style="width: 27.74%; padding: 0cm 5.4pt; border-width: medium 1pt 1pt medium; border-style: none solid solid none; border-right: 1pt solid rgb(127, 127, 127); border-bottom: 1pt solid rgb(127, 127, 127); text-align: left;"> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 16px;">Aftab Opel</span></p> </td> <td width="28%" valign="top" style="width: 28.76%; padding: 0cm 5.4pt; border-width: medium 1pt 1pt medium; border-style: none solid solid none; border-right: 1pt solid rgb(127, 127, 127); border-bottom: 1pt solid rgb(127, 127, 127); text-align: left;"><span style="font-size: 16px;">Head of Programmes</span></td> <td width="18%" valign="top" style="width: 18.8%; padding: 0cm 5.4pt; border-width: medium 1pt 1pt medium; border-style: none solid solid none; border-right: 1pt solid rgb(127, 127, 127); border-bottom: 1pt solid rgb(127, 127, 127); text-align: left;"> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">DD/MM/YYYY</font></p> </td> </tr> </tbody></table> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"></font><strong><font color="#ffb612" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">--- Guidance text, please delete down to the next heading ---</font></strong></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><em><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">The project statement is a very short&nbsp;outline of a project (maximum two pages) that a team is proposing to implement, subject to funding.&nbsp;</font></em></p> <h2><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"></font><font face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">1. Why?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 16px;">By default, poor people who live in hard to 
reach areas are deprived under multiple indicators of inequality laying with 
economic, social and cultural reasons. An estimated 14% of the population in 
Bangladesh lacks access to safe drinking water, while 43% lacks access to 
improved sanitation[1]. 
Although there are some improvements in last two decades, vulnerable pockets 
remain, including those living in hard to reach terrains or suffering from 
socioeconomic marginalisation due to poverty, gender or disability. Those most deprived 
from access to WASH are groups that are already vulnerable in socioeconomic 
terms: children, women and adolescent girls, the elderly and infirm, persons 
with disabilities, and the extreme poor. Deprivation of water and sanitation 
rights for these groups are made manifold by the close linkages of water and 
sanitation with health and education[2]. 
 
Under 
critical geographic consideration Fulchori upazila under Gaibandha district 
marks as one of the disaster vulnerable upazilas at the northwest district under 
Rangpur Division. The division has the highest proportion of poor in the 
country, with 30% of its population classified as being in the lowest of five 
wealth categories[3]. 
Most of the communities characterised by chars, or riverine islands formed by 
sedimentation, where a predominantly poor or extreme poor population live at 
constant risk of flooding and erosion, with little access to services and 
health and education infrastructure. The challenges of this area are evident in 
the Hard-to-Reach ranking conducted by the World Bank’s Water and Sanitation Program 
(WSP), which ranks all 7 unions in Fulchari upazila of Gaibandha, as extremely 
or very hard to reach.</span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 16px;"> 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
[1] WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring 
Programme, Progress on drinking water and sanitation: 2012 update. 
 
 
 
 
 
[2] DeFrancis, Marc P. 2012. Economic impacts of inadequate sanitation 
in Bangladesh. Water and Sanitation Program. Washington, DC: World Bank.  
 
 
 
 
 
[3] Bangladesh 2011 
Demographic and Health Survey Final Report 
 
.</span> 
 
 
 
</p> <h2><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"></font><font face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">2. What?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;">As WASH deprivation experienced by 
the most marginalized groups demand immediate response, interventions adopt a 
service-delivery approach. However, limitations of an exclusively 
hardware-based service delivery approach, includes creating dependency, poor 
self-reliance, lack of ownership by local communities and rampant corruption. Unless 
processes are improved by way of bottom-up changes in the local power dynamics 
where the government acts to address the local demand from rights holders in an 
transparent and accountable manner, universal accessibility of WASH cannot be 
ensured.  
 
Experiencing from the last 03 years 
implementation of HRBA pilot and following district wide approach, the project 
will extend its working areas rest of the union of same sub district with massive engagement of LGIs, upazila administration and integrate 
health and education actors in realising WASH.</span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">While there are wide complexity 
of issues that are leading the WASH deprivation of target communities, the project 
will focus to address the following pertinent causative factors: &nbsp; &nbsp;</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Lack 
of awareness of awareness of the community about the importance of WASH, its relation 
to health, the various WASH policies/programs of the government,&nbsp; their rights/entitlements, and lack of 
critical awareness of how the system works &nbsp;</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Limited 
or no CSOs working with local communities on WASH issue from a ‘rights 
perspective' &nbsp;</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Lack 
of involvement of the local communities in the planning, implementation and 
monitoring of WASH programs including poor budgetary allocation for WATSAN 
services</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Non-functioning 
WASH institutions, including lack of transparency, accountability and corruption</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Estimated cost: GBP 431,537</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Estimated timeframe: 36 months</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Existing WaterAid experience: WaterAid Bangladesh has implemented a pilot project with similar theme.</font></p> <h2><font face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">3. Where?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;">5 Unions of Fulchori upazila of Gaibandha district.</span><br><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"></font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 16px;">Target population: this project will work with the poor community, local government and local health care providers.</span></p> <h2><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"></font><font face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">4. Who?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Partner NGO is yet to be selected.</span></p></p></div><button class="accordion">Bangladesh | Rural Wash | Micro Finance for WASH Promotion | ImamurRahman@wateraid.org | target funding: GBP 300,000</button> <div class="panel"><p><h1 align="left" style="text-align: left;"><strong><font color="windowtext" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Project Statement</font></strong></h1> <h1 align="left" style="text-align: left;"><strong><font color="windowtext" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">WaterAid Bangladesh</font></strong></h1>  <table width="100%" style="width: 100%;" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"> <tbody><tr> <td width="24%" valign="top" style="ba