s proposing to implement, subject to funding.&nbsp;</font></em></p> <h2><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"></font><font face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">1. Why?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;">This project is aimed at transforming the lives of teagarden workers by improving 
their access to safe drinking water, improved sanitation and hygiene behaviour. 
In a survey, 
in some selected tea gardens in the area, only 3.5% workers’ household had 
access to improved sanitation and 53.7% practiced open defecation. With a very 
little improvement in the overall situation over a decade, teagarden workers are 
still excluded from the mainstream population and are deprived of many 
essential services including access to improved WASH services. For the tea 
garden workers and their families, stream water was the source of water for 
drinking, cleaning and bathing. Moreover, they had to openly defecate in the 
same place near the stream due to lack of access to water which is the main 
source of contamination of the water they use for various domestic purposes. 
Their rights and needs are yet to be addressed by the duty bearers and their 
children still deprived of education and basic health care services. As a 
result, they also lack awareness menstrual hygiene management, waste disposal, 
environmental sanitation and the importance of WASH in health and family 
wellbeing.&nbsp;  
 
The proposed project will be implemented in selected tea 
gardens of Sreemangal upazila of Moulvibazar district of Sylhet division in Bangladesh to support the 
excluded tea picker communities with WASH access and to help them raise their 
voice to claim WASH rights. The project will be implemented as a combination of 
