--</font></strong></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><em><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">The project statement is a very short&nbsp;outline of a project (maximum two pages) that a team is proposing to implement, subject to funding.&nbsp;</font></em></p> <h2><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"></font><font face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">1. Why?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"></font>&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 12pt;">Eighty seven percent people 
of Bangladesh have access to improved drinking water source, which is adjusted 
for Arsenic contamination in the ground water (JMP 2015). Despite progress on 
overall water coverage and achieving the MDG water target: access to safe water 
for all remains a challenge, particularly due to arsenic contamination. About 
20 million people drink water contaminated with Arsenic. In terms of 
sanitation, Bangladesh has seen a remarkable reduction in open defecation of 33 
percentage points from 1990 to 2015, to the current rate of 1% (JMP 2015). But 
it is to be noted that only 61% toilet can be categorized as improved toilet. 
And like the situation of water coverage, in hard to reach rural areas the percentage 
of improved toilet is much less than the national coverage. 
 
&nbsp; 
 
Water, sanitation and 
hygiene are fundamental to health, and these are even more crucial for child 
health. There has been significant progress in reducing child mortality 
globally but infectious diseases remain a big challenge for children. Diarrhoea 
is one of the major causes of death of under 5 children and around 90% of 
diarrhoeal cases are caused by poor WASH condition. 50% of under-nutrition is 
due to lack of WASH, and under-nutrition is an underlying risk factor for 
around 30% of under-five deaths. Repeated episodes of diarrhoea can make 
under-nourished children predisposed to pneumonia. A lack of hygiene and 
sanitation and the associated diarrhoea also contributes to stunting and inhibited 
cognitive development in millions of children worldwide. &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Ground water, which is the 
mostly used drinking water in Gangni upazila, is heavily 
contaminated with Arsenic. According to DPHE (Department of Public Health 
Engineering) 60% of the water points (tube wells) are contaminated with Arsenic 
in Meherpur. Many people are using Arsenic contaminated water for drinking and 
other purposes, and many collect Arsenic free water from existing deep tube 
well in the area which are usually far from their home. This use of Arsenic 
contaminated water poses great health risk, especially Arsenic contamination 
causes incidence of Arsenicosis disease which sometimes turns into cancer. 
Already there are incidence of death from Arsenicosis disease and many are 
still suffering. And alarmingly there are no specialized health services to 
treat the Arsenicosis patients in government health centers. Condition of 
sanitation and hygienic practices are also very poor in this area.&nbsp;</span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;"> 
 
</span></p> <h2><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"></font><font face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">2. What?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"></font>&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 12pt;">Main objectives of this project: 
 
- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">To improve WASH situation in the Community for 
enhancing health and nutrition status &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">To improve WASH situation in healthcare 
facilities for safe and convenient access to services &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">To strengthen knowledge of health workforce 
for improved and sustainable WASH&nbsp;</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">To sensitize LGIs, DPHE and&nbsp; 
healthcare providers and other stakeholders to address 
arsenic mitigation issues</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Project approach </font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"> 
 
This WASH in Health project 
is designed to contribute in achieving objectives of Rural Programme. In line 
with the Programme plan, the following strategic and operational approach will 
be followed in the project:  
 
&nbsp; 
 
</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">A.&nbsp;&nbsp; Rights Based Approach 
(RBA): </font><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Rural program has already incorporated the 
elements of rights especially with regards to WASH in all projects based on 
learning on HRBA pilot initiatives under rural program in last CP strategy 
(2011-16). Alongside, in line with equity and inclusion framework, elements has 
been consolidated and adopted in this project. Besides this, all further 
learnings will be documented that will enable us to remain responsive to new 
lessons.  
 
&nbsp; 
 
</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">B.&nbsp;&nbsp; District Wide Approach 
(DWA): </font><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">Making consistency with programme plan, this 
project will implement the District Wide Approach considering sub-district as 
unit of DWA targeting whole upazilas (sub-districts). Projects will be designed 
with a strong influencing and advocacy element so our interventions are 
recognised, taken up and replicated in sub-districts.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">C.&nbsp;&nbsp; Integrated Approach (IA): </font><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">This project will undertake integration in three different way i) 
Water, sanitation and hygiene will be integrated as one package, ii) 
Integrating WASH with health, nutrition and link with micro finance for 
sustainability. iii) Integration among the partners, media, other network 
platforms with mutual respect and accountability.  
 
&nbsp; 
 
</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">D.&nbsp;&nbsp; Sustainability Approach 
(SA): </font><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">WASH in Health project will work to sensitize 
local government institutions and respective authorities of institutions to 
solder responsibilities for necessary operation and maintenance of WASH 
interventions allocating and creating WASH fund. Besides this, established 
linkage with micro finance institutions to consider WASH as micro financing 
content, which contribute to improvisation of water and sanitation facilities 
as well as sustainability. Finally, the shift to RBA promotes greater long-term 
sustainability through placing O&amp;M within the broader framework of better 
systems and governance. 
 
&nbsp; 
</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"> 
E.&nbsp;&nbsp; 
Knowledge and Innovation Approach (KIA): 
</font><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">This project will capture the learning and disseminate among the sector actors 
to create evidence for further advocacy. Beside this, best practices will be 
scale up through horizontal learning. 
 
&nbsp; 
</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"> 
Implementation Strategy: </font><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">In WASH in Health project, Community Clinic- a government designed 
union level primary healthcare center is the center of the project strategy. 
Inclusive and sustainable WASH facilities will be installed at those healthcare 
centers to create example and advocacy initiatives will be taken with relevant 
stakeholders so that the example is replicated at other healthcare centers. 
Health care providers and other staffs of the facility will be trained so that 
they practice and disseminate messages on WASH in relation to health and 
nutrition towards the community people. Community groups formed in line with 
government instructions to support smooth service of community clinics will 
also be engaged and trained in the project so that they carry their 
responsibility smoothly. Catalysts will be developed in the community who will 
be crucial in taking forward the healthy home campaign in the intervention 
areas. Mothers of under 5 children will be a major targeted stakeholders to 
address the health and nutritional status of new born babies. Traditional Birth 
Attendants (TBA) and Skilled Birth Attendants (SBA), who are responsible for 
most of the deliveries in the project areas, will also be reached to ensure 
clean and safe delivery. Authority of Upazila health complex and persons from 
local health departments will be engaged which will help to produce necessary 
instructions and circular that might help for better implementation of the 
project. And for the Arsenic prone areas, DPHE (Department of Public Health 
Engineering) who are major stakeholders from government’s side, will be engaged 
in the project for initiating measures to mitigate arsenic contamination 
impacts. 
 
&nbsp; 
