="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><em><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">The project statement is a very short&nbsp;outline of a project (maximum two pages) that a team is proposing to implement, subject to funding.&nbsp;</font></em></p> <h2><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font><font style="font-size: 12pt;" face="Arial,sans-serif">1. Why?</font></h2><p style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-size: 14px;">The urban poor living 
in slums and low-income communities in major cities and municipalities in 
Bangladesh are deprived of basic utility services including water and 
sanitation. These populations suffer disproportionately from poor WASH and 
associated shortfalls in healthcare, reflected in a number of health indicators 
including exposure to waterborne diseases, nutrition, maternal and child 
mortality, and healthcare seeking behaviour. Poor WASH access and health 
problems have a number of knock-on impacts on livelihood, productivity, income, 
and dignity. Growing morbidity leads to loss of work days, rising healthcare 
costs, and loss of productive time in collecting water or using sanitation 
facilities. However, it is evident that the provision of access to safe and 
adequate WASH can contribute to reducing the disease burden of the urban poor, 
and thus limit the overall impact on pubic and environmental health. Evidences 
suggest that improved water supply reduces diarrhoea morbidity by 21%, 
ascariasis by 29%, hookworm infection by 4%, trachoma morbidity by 27%, while 
additional improvement of drinking water quality would lead to a reduction of 
diarrhoea by 45%. Improved sanitation reduces diarrhoea morbidity by 37.5%.[1] 
Improved access to these services creates significant health outcomes[2] &amp; economic benefits[3] &amp; is considered to be one of the primary drivers of public health.[4] &nbsp;The project aims to 
contribute to improved health and resilience of WASH-deprived urban poor living 
in slums and low income settlements of three cities and three municipal towns 
of Bangladesh. 
 
To achieve this goal, 
the expected outcomes of the project are: WASH deprivation and 
public health risks reduced among target communities through increased access 
to climate/ disaster resilient, community-based WASH services. Effectiveness of urban 
primary healthcare clinic sand service delivery in target cities and towns 
improved through WASH integration 
 
· Policy and practice on 
resilient WASH and its integration in health services improved for urban poor 
through evidence based and collective advocacy.</span></p><p style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;[1] WHO and UNICEF. (2004) Meeting the MDG drinking water and sanitation target- a mid-term 
assessment of progress. 
 
 
 
 
 
[2] Brown J, Cairncross S and Ensink JHJ. (2013) Water, sanitation, hygiene and enteric infections in children. Arch 
Dis Child.doi:10.1136/archdischild-2011-301528 
 
 
 
 
 
[3] Haller L, Hutton G and Bartram J. (2007) Estimating 
the costs and health benefits of water and sanitation improvements at global 
level. J Water Health,&nbsp;5(4). 
 
 
 
 
 
[4] WHO and UNICEF. (2004) Meeting the MDG drinking water and sanitation target- a mid-term 
assessment of progress. 
 
