Over the last years, 
Ethiopia has registered significant achievements in increasing enrollment rates. 
However, Increase in student enrolment was not matched with WASH facilities, as 
priorities were given to expansion of schools nearby communities. In Ethiopia, school water coverage 
estimated at 39% and sanitation coverage at 37% (UNICEF, 2015 report).  
 
Ethiopia has national 
standards for WASH in Schools. Several highlights of Ethiopia’s national 
standards include: pupils per latrine/toilet and pupils per hand washing stand 
are the same—50 students to 1 latrine/toilet. However, it is only 21% of 
schools meet the official standard for pupils per latrine/toilet. On 
average, the toilet/student ratio is 1:120. (UNICEF, 2015). Similarly, only 7% of schools meet the official standard for pupils per hand washing 
stand. The government standard for provision of water for drinking and hygiene 
per pupil per day at schools is 15 litres/pupil.&nbsp; However, it is only 16% of schools meet this 
standard. However, there is an effort to increase 
girls’ school enrollment, lack of basic needs, as sanitary pads that facilitate 
routine activities of girls at early adolescence are observed to deter girls’ 
school-attendance in rural Ethiopia. Special support for girl students, 
especially when they have their first menstruation and separate functioning 
sanitary facilities are necessities that should be in school at all times if 
gender equality and girls’ empowerment is to be achieved. 
 
WaterAid advocates that governments must meet their 
obligations to protect and realise each child’s rights to WASH and education, 
and therefore take the lead to improve WASH in schools in the long term.&nbsp; WaterAid seeks to work in a way that 
recognises these power relations, empowers people excluded from services, 
creating an environment of accountability among duty bearers and service 
providers, embedding this through the strengthening of systems, culture and 
mechanisms for participation and accountability. WA aims to achieve sustainable 
and inclusive school WASH through joined-up programming, which combines 
practical interventions on the ground with capacity building, learning and 
advocacy. WaterAid’s WASH in school programming focuses on three interlinking 
themes, the enabling environment, 
quality implementation and sustainable management. 
 
This project will 
contribute to outcome four which states “WASH systems are integrated with other sectors” under the Sustainability 
