that only 32% of schools and health institutions have access to improved water 
and sanitation facilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;  
 
&nbsp; 
 
Lack of access to 
WASH services have multiple impacts including health, education, environment, 
equity and achieving of sustainable development goals. It also affects children’s ability to learn in several ways. Diseases 
related to poor WASH are common in Ethiopia. Helminth (worm) infections affect 
many children, can force children to be absent from school, impair physical 
development and reduce children’s cognitive development through pain and 
discomfort, competition for nutrients, anaemia, and damage to tissues and 
organs. Diarrhoeal diseases force many schoolchildren to be absent from school. 
Girls and boys likely affected by different ways and this may contribute to 
unequal learning opportunities.  
 
&nbsp; 
 
Lack of adequate and 
separate facilities for menstrual hygiene can contribute to girls missing days 
at school; this, compounded with social factors, can even lead girls to 
dropping out of education altogether at puberty. Study showed that annual 
dropout rate of adolescent girls was 14.2% unavailability of WASH service was 
one factor (2012). A study done in Ethiopia showed that girls miss 2 to 3 school days 
per month including exams due to menstruation (2012).  
 
&nbsp; 
 
Children with 
disabilities are likely to be affected, resulting in situations where a disabled 
child might not eat or drink all day to avoid needing the toilet, leading to 
health problems and eventually to their dropping out of school. An analysis of 
the annual report of Ministry of Education showed that separate toilets (for 
girls) are associated with a smaller dropout rate especially in secondary 
school girls need for greater privacy in sanitation and hygiene when they reach 
puberty (2012).  
 
&nbsp; 
 
Low levels of water and sanitation coverage also have 
important social implications. Women and children spend several hours every day 
fetching water. The time spent fetching water could be used to care for 
children in the home, rest or employment in income generating activities. For 
girls, the task of carrying water combined with lack of sanitary facilities in 
schools often stands in the way of their education and traveling long hours to 
remote sources exposes girls to increase rates of abduction and rape. 
 
Lack of resources, 
capacity to plan, implement and maintain WASH services at district/community 
levels, coordination, and lack of effective hygiene promotion are the major 
barriers that hinder access to WASH in Ethiopia.</p> <h2><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"></font><font face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">2. What?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font color="#ffb612" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;"> 
 
