As a country, Ethiopia is highly exposed and vulnerable to climate change 
impacts. An 
assessment made by Vincent (2004) shows that Ethiopia ranks the 7th vulnerable 
country in Africa to the impact of climate change[1]. 
Climate 
change models agree that Ethiopia will become hotter with more extreme rainfall 
and - yet - unknown risk of major impacts in some regions.&nbsp; Extreme rainfall events will simultaneously 
increase flooding events and drought periods.&nbsp; 
In some regions, seasonal rainfall may drastically reduce or shift which 
will have an adverse effect on water security and livelihoods of the most 
marginalized[2].&nbsp; Water is predicted to be the main channel through which the 
impacts of climate change will be felt by people, the ecosystem and economics. 
However, predicting impacts on the availability and quality of water and 
sanitation remains difficult.  
 
&nbsp; 
 
Bale 
- like the other parts of Ethiopia – is affected by the impact of climate 
change, particularly changes in temperature and rainfall predictability. Gololcha 
Woreda is one of 18 Woredas in Bale zone with a population of 127,183 (CSA 
2016).&nbsp; The Water supply and improved 
sanitation coverages are about 46% and 22% respectively. The Woreda has also 
the largest prevalence of trachoma (47%) which shows hygiene behaviour is also 
low.&nbsp; The selected target kebeles - Metur 
and Urgessa kebeles are located in lowland areas, and highly affected by the 
effects of climate change. The Kebele people are using water from unprotected 
ponds, and the school and health post do not have improved water and sanitation 
services. Moreover, an NGO or government program does not exist to support the 
community and alleviate these WASH related problems. 
 
&nbsp; 
 
&nbsp; 
 
WaterAid 
recognizes the need for an integrated approach to WASH, climate change and 
water security. A changing climate will worsen existing threats to water security, 
which include present day climate variability, weak governance of WASH 
services, weak governance of water resources, environmental degradation, 
growing demand for water and threats to water quality, such as pollution and 
salinity[3]. 
 
&nbsp; 
 
WaterAid believes that without a focus on climate resilience in WASH 
systems and programming, significant gains in WASH access made over the past 
years will start to erode; sustained universal access to WASH will not be 
achieved and this will act as a brake on the goal of ending extreme poverty in 
Ethiopia[4]. 
 
&nbsp; 
 
This project 
will contribute to outcome 1 – i.e. Climate resilience is adopted in programmes of WASH 
and other Sectors under the Water Resilience and Climate change 
Programme.  
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
