in Education Programme by: improving implementation of existing WASH in schools 
policies and plans by 2020. Through greater participation of students, teachers, 
and communities in advocating for implementation of existing policies on the rights 
to WASH in schools, this project will strengthen WASH service delivery in 
schools. Aligned to the global strategy 
with its focus on hygiene, the WASH Rights and Hygiene Campaigns Project aims 
to demystify taboos about MHM that hinders prioritization in the implementation 
of policies that ensure the rights of women and girls are realized. To ensure a 
holistic approach to hygiene, which also community centered, the project will 
utilize our Endogenous Development approach to develop and utilize culturally 
appropriate behaviour change communication processes.</span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p> <h2><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font><font style="font-size: 12pt;" face="Arial,sans-serif">2. What?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font><span style="font-size: 12pt;">This project will develop the capacity of school children to 
be effective agents of behaviour change. &nbsp;For example, the project will support the 
formation of school Health and Gender clubs and establish a School WASH Drama 
series. Menstrual Hygiene Management will be a central hygiene theme in this 
project. 
 
The project will also enable the students to be advocates 
for social change, especially in relation to WASH.&nbsp; For instance , the Children WASH Parliament will 
be scaled up in partner districts and regions. The children WASH Parliament 
concept is an advocacy platform for children to engage duty bearers regarding 
the integration of WASH into the educational system ranging from facilities 
construction to inclusion in the curriculum. WAG will provide technical support 
to make this happen. The project will strengthen the capacity of students to 
conduct “community” applied-action research, which will be linked to the School 
WASH Policy Dialogue Series. (This is also an advocacy platform to influence 
WASH policies in the educational sector). &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 16px;">The specific activities to implemented are:&nbsp;</span><span style="font-size: 16px;">Action Research (Study on School WASH 
Status), Capacity strengthening on advocacy and Behaviour Change Communication for 
School Health and Gender clubs, Parent-Teacher Association and the School Management Committees, School WASH Drama series, WASH in Schools Policy Dialogues, &nbsp;Children WASH 
Parliament, and WASH Rights Campaigns</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Estimated cost</font></strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">&nbsp;–GBP20,000</font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Estimated timeframe</font></strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">&nbsp;–24 months</font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Existing WaterAid experience</font></strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">&nbsp;– Less than 2 years’ experience</font><span style="font-size: 12pt;"></span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">&nbsp;</font></p> <h2><font style="font-size: 12pt;" face="Arial,sans-serif">3. Where?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The project will be in implemented in Greater Accra and Western Region. This will be targeting school children, parents and influential members of the communities where the project will focus as well as policy decision makers- Members of Parliaments in the areas of focus and specific parliamentary select committees; the Metropolitan Municipal and District Assemblies (MMDAs) in project areas; Ghana Health Service and Ghana Education Service officials (National-District level).&nbsp;</span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif" style="font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</font></p> <h2><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font><font style="font-size: 12pt;" face="Arial,sans-serif">4. Who?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001p