&nbsp;(5)&nbsp; Design and studies on the construction of the faecal sludge 
management system: Extraction – Transport – Treatment – Post-treatment use 
 
&nbsp;(6)&nbsp; Implementing the project including the BCD / ABCDE approach for 
integrated hygiene promotion  
 
&nbsp;(7)&nbsp; Conducting end-line Survey 
</p><p style="margin-bottom: 0pt;"> 
 
Estimated cost – This project is fully 
unfunded. The estimated cost is 3,975,800,000 
Ar. (1,047,000 £) 
</p><p style="margin-bottom: 0pt;"> 
 
The total duration of the project 
is&nbsp;3 years. This means&nbsp;35 month of which there will be an annual planning of 
activities of 12 months each year 
</p><p style="margin-bottom: 0pt;"> 
 
Existing WaterAid experience – During the past 3 years, WaterAid Madagascar has implemented 
4 small-scale faecal sludge management systems, 2 systems in the Atsinanana 
region (Mahanoro and Vatomandry), 1 in the Analamanga region (Manjakandriana) 
and 1 system in the Menabe region (Morondava). These projects are currently 
managed by small local operators who are at the same time partners in the 
sanitation marketing project. Their businesses have been successful because 
they have continually improved their products quality and diversified the 
products and services they offer to consumers. Good entrepreneurial spirit, 
sound management knowledge and leadership in business plan development and 
implementation have been seen as the key to their successes. As such they did 
not only provide products and services but also added other packages such as 
faecal sludge management. 
 
</p><p style="margin-bottom: 0pt;">&nbsp;</p> <h2><font style="font-size: 12pt;" face="Arial,sans-serif">3. Where?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0pt;"><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font> 
 
The project will be implemented in Municipality 
of Sabotsinamehana, District of Antananarivo Avaradrano, Analamanga Region. 
 
The project will target 250,000 
direct and indirect users in Antananarivo and neighbouring municipalities 
 
</p><p style="margin-bottom: 0pt;">&nbsp;</p> <h2><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font><font style="font-size: 12pt;" face="Arial,sans-serif">4. Who?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0pt;"><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font> 
 
Local authorities’ 
involvement since the beginning of the project is important. As owner of the 
infrastructure, local authorities are primarily responsible for donating or 
making the treatment site available. They are also responsible for monitoring 
the system put in place and the use of the emptying equipment made available to 
operators. Municipal authorities are also responsible for disseminating 
municipal sanitation decrees. 
 
We will carry out 
technological tests on the sludge extraction equipment and tools and on the 
transport means locally available. We will also identify and select the 
appropriate local operators with motivation and expertise in emptying to ensure 
the sustainability and ownership of the service to be set up. During this 
period, we will also seek technical advice and support from WaterAid's Regional 
Technical Advisor on how to improve the processes and technical aspects of the 
emptying service to be set up.&nbsp;  
 
After identifying 
the appropriate operators and tested technology for pumping faecal sludge from 
latrines, we will start working with municipalities and new local private operators 
on the actual setting up of the complete chain of the emptying service in the 
intervention municipality. 
 
