to 27,741 people, covers an area of 1,660 km² (Source: Municipal census 2013) 
and with a population density of 357 people per km². Average household size is 
6 people. In 2015, WASH access rate was estimated at 27.31% (Source: SESAME – 
The National WASH Database). On the other hand, the Budget Programme Per 
Regional Objective (BPOR) 2016 concluded that access rate to water was 43.61% 
and sanitation 71.39%. 
 
&nbsp; 
 
Equipped with a dynamic and committed team, the municipality has 
achieved these results in terms of access thanks to collaboration with 
technical and financial partners. On the other hand, the lack of a sector 
development plan, corresponding budgets and lack of cohesion between actors 
deprive the municipality of advocacy and coordination tools for mobilizing new 
technical and financial partners and collaboration between actors. There is no 
clear and sustainable funding mechanism for the sector either in terms of own 
or external resources. Financial and technical partners’ interventions are 
guided by the needs identified by the donors rather than an overall vision of 
change coordinated by the respective municipalities. The scale of existing 
infrastructure witness previous efforts in terms of service delivery, but the 
municipality is increasingly facing problems due to the need for rehabilitation 
and upgrading of existing services. Each actor has their own diagnosis but 
there is no reliable system to assess the situation of the whole set of 
services and to design the actions to be taken to attain universal access.  
 
&nbsp; 
 
In terms of citizen participation in the development process in 
Madagascar, it was found that civil society organizations (CSOs) in the sector 
are not yet well organized to have significant influence on decision-making, 
although there are isolated initiatives for structuring and mobilization at 
both the local and national levels, notably the creation of the structure 
bringing together the CSOs working in the Water, Sanitation and Hygiene sector, 
which gathers CSOs from the 22 regions, in 2015. This weakness of the civil 
society is reflected in the almost non-existence of relays and appealing force 
to key authorities at all levels. Additionally, there is a lack of awareness of 
participatory practices and a lack of transparency in the administration. 
 
&nbsp; 
 
The majority of the population of the municipality of Manjakandriana 
has been deprived of drinking water for a long time and also deprived of adequate 
WASH services. 
 
&nbsp; 
 
At the municipal and regional levels, WASH advocacy actions often 
took place through the Diorano-WASH platform, which is composed of national and 
international civil society actors, the private sector and state actors. 
Confusion has existed regarding the authorities and the audience of advocacy 
messages conveyed by the platform, given that these authorities were at the 
same time members of the platform, hence the need for the establishment of a 
separate CSO network from the Diorano-WASH platform. In the case of 
Manjakandriana, the Municipal Diorano-WASH Committee has yet to be set up at 
the same time as the WASH CSO network in the municipality.  
 
&nbsp; 
 
In terms of civil 
society capacities and operationalization, recommendations were issued during 
the consultation workshops and the establishment of these regional and national 
WASH CSO networks. These recommendations were on the need to strengthen WASH 
CSO networks through the inventorying of local CSOs and recruitment of members, 
capacity building in citizen engagement and mobilization, as well as 
fundraising and sustainability of actions initiated.</span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;"></span><br><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font></p> <h2><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font><font style="font-size: 12pt;" face="Arial,sans-serif">2. What?</font></h2> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font>&nbsp;<strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Project theme</font></strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">For the municipality, this project 
will help tackle the problems of management by the municipality, which used to 
be dictated by the mayor's populism to the detriment of the service 
sustainability, and at the same time benefit from JIRAMA's service quality 
skills already proved throughout the major cities of Madagascar. For the WASH 
sector in Madagascar, this collaboration with JIRAMA will demonstrate the 
effectiveness of the urban model promoted by WaterAid to develop more and more 
water resources upstream of JIRAMA against the usual practices of only 
supporting JIRAMA in terms of water distribution. Regarding sanitation, we will 
develop sanitation marketing and faecal Sludge Management (FSM) in the 
administrative centre of the municipality as well as in the surroundings which 
are more rural. We will implement our integrated hygiene promotion strategy 
based on the BCD / ABCDE approaches. Finally, this project will implement the 
integrated approach to WASH, which will essentially promote hygiene along with 
other components such as health, education, nutrition, maternal health, newborn 
and child health (Multiple Use of water Services (MUS), Village Savings and 
Loans Associations (VSLA), etc.). 
 
&nbsp; 
 
Special efforts will be made to the 
municipality in order to strengthen the collaboration systems between WASH 
stakeholders and others to achieve WASH universal access. The municipal team 
will be strengthened to play its role of sector coordinator and infrastructure 
owner responsible for setting up the services, meeting qualities and 
maintaining existing services. Support will be provided at the strategic level 
to lead sector actors towards universal access by setting up joint planning 
mechanisms, monitoring service quality, increasing coverage, developing a 
periodic review mechanism to build a joint overview of the situation regarding 
universal access and the actions to be taken to achieve it, and finally a 
sustainable fundraising strategy mobilising local and external resources.  
 
&nbsp; 
 
Our approach will be 
based on citizens’ commitment to the process of achieving WASH universal 
access. This project aims to contribute to strengthening Civil Society 
Organizations and to establishing a balance of powers enabling WASH universal 
access. Specifically, WASH sector functioning and decision-making process at 
the municipal level will be strengthened and involve citizens through an 
organized and strengthened civil society, inclusive spaces for dialogue between 
CSOs and local authorities, as well as the proactivity and accountability of 
local authorities with regard to the realization of the rights to water, 
sanitation and hygiene.</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Estimated cost</font></strong></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">This project will cost £1,141,599 which is Fully unfunded (Ar4,338,079,000 in local currency)</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Estimated timeframe</font></strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">&nbsp;– 36 months</font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">Existing WaterAid experience</font></strong><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif"></font></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><font style="font-size: 12pt;" color="black" face="Arial,sans-serif">WaterAid has already worked in this 
municipality in 2014-2016 for the implementation of WASH project in 4 fokontany 
