enabling structures such as Area Development Committees (ADCs) and Village 
Development Committees (VDCs) that are supposed to support citizens to demand 
their rights to WASH are not functional. The citizens are also not well 
informed regarding their right to development as provided for in legal and 
policy frameworks including the Local Government Act. This has affected 
participation of communities in their own development as evidenced by the limited 
evidence of marginalised citizen challenging decisions that negatively affect 
their lives. This is further aggravated by high levels of illiteracy among 
citizens and lack of knowledge and skills among duty bearers to ably engage 
with citizens leading to limited responsiveness and accountability. Although in 
essence Civil Society Organisations are supposed to play a critical role in the 
empowerment of citizens, their focus on delivering services has limited their 
ability to effectively organise citizens for collective action on service 
provision gaps within the districts. In the long run poor and marginalised 
communities and other groups have been left behind in the provision of services.</span></p><p style="text-align: justify; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 14px;">The key issues this project will aim to address. 
