Swat, once a scenic district of Khyber Pakhtun Khawah(KPK), ha suffered dire loss of 
infrastructure &amp; services, owing to the consecutive disasters in the form 
of earthquake, insurgency and devastating flood. According to humanitarian 
survey,[1] almost 70% of the 
institutions (Schools/Health Facilities) have inadequate WATSAN facilities. 
Lack of access to safe water, poor sanitation, and improper liquid and solid 
waste disposal are key contributors to widely prevalent under nutrition. One fourth of the children in are underweight. 
Vitamin A deficiency in children is 68.5% while iron and zinc deficient 
children are 49% and 45.4% respectively. Similarly, Vitamin A deficient 
pregnant mothers are 76.2% while in pregnant women iron and zinc deficiency 
persists 30% and 52.6% respectively[2].KPK 
has lower level of safer water usage at household (70%) as compared to national 
level (87%). Usage of hygienic facility is lower (62%) than the national level 
(66%).[3] 
 
&nbsp; 
 
WASH is known critical factor for breaking the chronic vicious 
cycle of illness and under nutrition. Young children and school going boys 
&amp; girls are highly susceptible to chronic malnutrition and stunting due to 
repeated infections and under-nutrition. The situation is no better at 
institutions (schools &amp; health facilities). Baseline study conducted during 
EPS’s School WASH program (DFID funded grant implemented by local partner EPS in collaboration with WaterAid Pakistan) shows that in schools, 55% of the water sources are 
not functional. In 97% of the cases, no microbiological tests and in 95% cases 
there were no Chemical or radiological tests conducted to know the water 
quality at the schools. 93% of the schools have insufficient and improper 
latrines and waste management system.  
 
&nbsp; 
 
Adolescent Girls lack information 
about nutrition, sanitation and menstrual hygiene management (MHM). On average 
23% students remained absent during menstruation. Adolescence is important 
period for a girl child as she enters active reproductive age and owing to 
social norm of early marriage will soon become a pregnant and lactating mother. 
Poor nutrition at this crucial period leads to micronutrient deficiencies and 
malnutrition of mother and child. Open defecation in surrounding communities of 
such schools is common which have high risk of environmental diseases. Urinary 
tract infection and dysentery are common among the girls. The burden of 
under-nutrition in children has lifelong negative consequences, including 
stunted growth and impaired cognitive development. These can permanently 
disable a child’s potential to become a productive adult. Nutrition is ignored 
area both at community and institutional level. Iron deficiency impairs mental 
development of &gt;40% of developing world's infants.[4] 
 
&nbsp; 
 
It is essential to develop an integrated 
programmatic approach to prioritize improved health and nutrition by using 
nutrition sensitive WASH interventions, while working at all the levels 
(facility, community, policy...etc). Only a holistic multi-sectoral integration 
can effectively address the interlinked and interdependent WASH, Health and 
Nutrition issues.</span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12px;" face="Arial,sans-serif" color="black"> 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
