like any other African countries experiences climate variability, which threatens 
the lives and prosperity of people across the country. The data show that 
temperatures are on the increase since 1960, and observations of rainfall shows 
statistically significant decreasing trends in annual rainfall (3.3% decrease 
per decade on average) (McSweeney et al., 2010c) and is projected that in 
future average temperatures will continue to rise (by 1.5-4.5°C by 2090s). Continued 
climatic change will significantly affect fresh water resources. Studies have 
shown that among the impacts happening and likely to happen include water 
logging, water pollution, increasing and/or decreasing river flow in some 
basins, drying up of some water bodies, intrusion of sea water into fresh water 
bodies including groundwater (URT, 2007). In the recent past, 2/3 of rivers in 
Tanzania have had reduced water volume as a result of decreased rainfall 
(Orindi and Murray, 2005). However, while Pangani and Ruvu rivers are projected 
to have a decrease in water flow, Rufiji, will have a slight increase 
(Mwandosya, et, al 1998).&nbsp; Nationally 
nevertheless water flow is projected to become more seasonal and scarce. Other 
studies have predicted that by 2025 the availability of fresh water in Tanzania 
will reduce to half the rates of 1990. The projection is that water flow change 
will be between 5 to 10% in all basins in Tanzania (Mwandosya, et al., 1998). Either 
most small rivers and springs have disappeared or become seasonal as a result 
there has been a steady encroachment into wetlands and water bodies in the 
country (URT, 2007).  
 
Changes in water flow in 
basins have already caused some socio-economic (for example, the 2005/6 drought 
affected millions of people and had a cost of at least 1% of GDP ) and 
ecological impacts in the country such as domestic water shortage and lower 
agricultural productivity due to increasing droughts in many parts of the country. 
Further deterioration in water availability will have major effects in Tanzania 
where already some communities are walking long distances looking for water. 
Sustaining access to safe water is increasingly difficult due to inadequate 
sustainability measures related to protection of water resources, inadequate 
capacity of communities manage water points whereby by 2017 over 35% of the 
constructed water points are not functioning. Moreover, the warming up and changes 
in rainfall patterns potentially affect groundwater recharge with considerable 
hydrological implications in most of the drought prone areas like the 
capital-Dodoma, entirely depends of the groundwater systems.  
 
While climatic change is both socially and 
economically posing major risks on survival of Tanzanians, the country is not 
well equipped to deal with existing climate risks. The study; “The Cost of Climate Change in Tanzania: 
Impacts and Adaptations” (2010) &nbsp;concludes that rural dwellers in Tanzania are 
more vulnerable to the effects of climate change than urban dwellers partly 
because of their limited resources, poor exposure to various technologies and 
their overdependence on natural resources which are threatened by climate 
change. Specific groups, which will be affected more, 
include women and girls who takes bigger responsibilities of ensuring water is 
available at home and therefore will continue spending less time on economic 
activities in search of water for domestic use. Youths will equally be affected 
as fewer employment opportunities will be in agriculture and other sectors 
affected by climate change including water and sanitation. &nbsp;</span></p>   <h1 style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt;"><span><font color="#009fda" face="Arial" size="5">2. What?</font></span></h1><p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 12px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">&nbsp;(i)&nbsp;</span><span style="font-size: 12px;">To generate knowledge 
on the impact of climatic change on WASH services through research/study. A 
number of studies including referenced above have done well on developing 
understanding on the impact of climatic change on water resources but there is 
less knowledge on how climate change has impacted at service level. We will 
conduct a comprehensive baseline to establish this knowledge to inform further 
the design of this project and the sector as well.</span></p><p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 12px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">(ii) Enhance rural 
community’s resilience to the impact of climate change on WASH access, through 
piloting and scaling up low carbon and low operations and mainaintainance 
technologies. The project will emphasize on solar pumping systems for 
rural for rural water supply systems, which among others have the following 
advantages Lower 
life cycle cost compared to diesel, O&amp;M cost is much lower compared to diesel 
powered systems, approriate for the rural settings because is easier to 
maintain and repair, the technology is environmentally friendly; no carbon 
emission and can be upgraded to match water system needs. The project will also 
emphasize on scaling up the electronic water payment systems, 
which has been piloted by WaterAid in collaboration with a private sector 
company in two districts and Manyara and Arusha regions.&nbsp; The electronic payment system has the 
following advantages; guarantees 100%&nbsp; 
collection of user fees and makes money available for O&amp;M, guarantee 
24/7 access to water supply and therefore communities, especially women and girls 
can use their time well in other activities. The system allows remote 
monitoring of the water points functionality and therefore guaranteeing timely 
and reliable repair maintenance of water systems, reduces re-investment cost of 
the Government especially when the system breaks up, collected money can repair 
and allow the Government funds to be channelled to new projects, Provides real 
time data which is useful for the water point mapping updating system of the 
Government. The project will also emphasize on large-scale rainwater harvesting as an alternative measure to reduce stress on 
the current water sources. While promoting the 
above technologies we will work in partnership with the private sector companies, 
vocational training institutions locally, and international to develop local 
knowledge and skills on designing, assembling and installation of the 
prioritized technologies.&nbsp; Through these partnerships, 
we will develop a hub of local technical capacities and jobs will be created 
for youths, both men and women. </span></p><p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 12px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">(iii) To 
